@congwang I agree. This solution does not look nice to me either.

@srkukarni @congwang I have a theory about the cause of "memory leak". If one does not call `Clear` on `Message`, used space in `Message` will not be zero'ed out. So next time we add tuple in it, `Message` thinks it does not have enough space and will enlarge the strings in itself. C++ STL will reserve extra space in string when you append (just like how it uses some heuristics to reserve extra space for vector). Thus we are always allocating extra memory here. 

If my theory is correct, https://github.com/twitter/heron/pull/2057 should solve the issues, along with this PR.

See our heap leak check graph below and [backtrace we get from core dump](https://gist.github.com/objmagic/13a59d0efcc7dcacd096dec59fd9d720#file-bt-L15) for details.
